Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Holds the lexer cursor and source pointer. Position tracking is
byte-based (not char-based) so the lexer can walk UTF-8 encoded
source without decoding each codepoint twice. Line/column are kept
for diagnostic positioning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five-field record: source (pointer to source bytes), position
(byte offset), line (1-based source line), column (1-based source
column), length (total source byte count - cached to avoid repeated
strlen calls).
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code string
    position as Integer        Note: Current position
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number
    length as Integer          Note: Source code length
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token record produced by the lexer for each lexical unit. Storing
line, column, and length per token lets diagnostics later reconstruct
the exact source span without re-scanning, which is critical for the
error reporting layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five-field record: type (TOKEN_* constant), lexeme (string pointer
to token text), line (1-based), column (1-based), length (byte count
of the lexeme).
@End Implementation
Type called "JuliaToken":
    type as Integer            Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer          Note: Token text
    line as Integer            Note: Line number
    column as Integer          Note: Column number
    length as Integer          Note: Lexeme length
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds a fresh JuliaLexer at byte offset 0, line 1, column 1. The
source length is cached up front so the inner loops never need to
re-measure the source string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40-byte JuliaLexer record. Returns 0 on failure. Calls
string_length once to precompute source length. Writes: source @0,
position @8 = 0, line @16 = 1, column @24 = 1, length @32. Returns
the lexer pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer_size be 40  Note: JuliaLexer: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1  Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, source_length

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming look at the current byte. Returns 0 at EOF so callers
can use a single equality check rather than a separate bounds test
on every character.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source @0, position @8, length @32 from the lexer. If
position >= length, returns 0 (EOF sentinel). Otherwise reads byte
at source+position via memory_get_byte and returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, pos

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
One-byte lookahead beyond the current cursor. Used to disambiguate
multi-char tokens like "<=" vs "<" or ".." vs ".".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source/position/length. If position+1 >= length, returns 0.
Otherwise reads byte at source+position+1.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_next_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If pos plus 1 is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, pos plus 1

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bumps cursor by one byte and updates column. Note that line tracking
is NOT done here - advance_line is the separate primitive for that
because tokens may contain embedded line breaks (e.g. multi-line
strings) and the lexer needs to call advance_line independently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position @8 and column @24. Writes position+1 and column+1
back. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let col be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, col plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Updates line counter and resets column to 1. Called separately from
advance_char because the caller knows whether the current byte is a
newline (\n) vs an ordinary byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads line @16, increments, writes back. Resets column @24 to 1.
Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_line" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: Reset column

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocator for JuliaToken records. Centralising the allocation
keeps the field offsets in one place and ensures the layout matches
the JuliaToken type declaration above.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes. Returns 0 on failure. Stores type @0, lexeme
@8, line @16, column @24, length @32. Returns the token pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:

    Let token_size be 40  Note: JuliaToken: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, length

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recognises the three Julia whitespace characters that are NOT newlines
(space, tab, CR). Newline is handled separately because it triggers
line/column accounting that whitespace skip-loops should not perform.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for byte 32 (space), 9 (tab), or 13 (CR); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:

    If ch is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-purpose predicate so callers can trigger advance_line on a
positive result rather than gating on byte literal 10.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for byte 10 (\n); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_newline" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:

    If ch is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit predicate. Julia also accepts unicode digits in some
contexts, but the lexer's number-tokeniser only handles ASCII to
keep the inner loop fast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if 48 <= ch <= 57 (ASCII '0'..'9'); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start predicate. Returns true for ASCII letters A-Z, a-z,
underscore, and a generous range of basic Unicode characters (treated
as identifier-allowed) since Julia explicitly allows non-ASCII names.
The Unicode pass is approximate: any byte >= 128 is accepted, which
correctly handles UTF-8 continuation bytes but does not validate full
codepoints. That tradeoff matches the Julia reference lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for: 65..90 (A-Z), 97..122 (a-z), 95 (underscore), and any
byte >= 128 (assumed Unicode). Returns 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: A-Z
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: a-z
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: underscore
    If ch is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check for Unicode letters (comprehensive Unicode support)
    If ch is greater than 127:
        Note: Check for common Unicode letter ranges
        Note: Latin Extended-A (U+0100-U+017F)
        If ch is greater than or equal to 256 and ch is less than or equal to 383:
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: Latin Extended-B (U+0180-U+024F)
        If ch is greater than or equal to 384 and ch is less than or equal to 591:
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: Greek and Coptic (U+0370-U+03FF)
        If ch is greater than or equal to 880 and ch is less than or equal to 1023:
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: Cyrillic (U+0400-U+04FF)
        If ch is greater than or equal to 1024 and ch is less than or equal to 1279:
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: Accept other high Unicode as potential letters
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-continuation predicate: alpha + digit + Julia-specific
characters like "!" (end-of-mutating-function-name marker). Used by
the identifier tokeniser after the first character has already
passed is_alpha.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha and is_digit; returns 1 on either positive. Also
returns 1 for byte 33 (!) per Julia's ident rule allowing "func!".
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with ch
    Let digit be proc is_digit with ch

    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If digit is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Julia allows ! in identifier names
    If ch is equal to 33:  Note: !
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Julia has ~50 reserved keywords. After the identifier tokeniser
collects a name, this routine compares it against every keyword to
decide whether the token type should be the generic TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
or the specific keyword constant (TOKEN_FUNCTION, TOKEN_IF, ...).
Sequential strcmp is fast enough given the bounded keyword count
and shorter average lexeme length.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each known keyword, allocates a comparison string and calls
string_equals; on match returns the corresponding TOKEN_* constant.
Falls through to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER if no keyword matches.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a Julia keyword

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "function":
        Return TOKEN_FUNCTION
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "end":
        Return TOKEN_END
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "if":
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "elseif":
        Return TOKEN_ELSEIF
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "else":
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "for":
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "while":
        Return TOKEN_WHILE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "do":
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "begin":
        Return TOKEN_BEGIN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "let":
        Return TOKEN_LET
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "try":
        Return TOKEN_TRY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "catch":
        Return TOKEN_CATCH
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "finally":
        Return TOKEN_FINALLY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "return":
        Return TOKEN_RETURN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "break":
        Return TOKEN_BREAK
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "continue":
        Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "struct":
        Return TOKEN_STRUCT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "mutable":
        Return TOKEN_MUTABLE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "abstract":
        Return TOKEN_ABSTRACT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "primitive":
        Return TOKEN_PRIMITIVE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "type":
        Return TOKEN_TYPE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "module":
        Return TOKEN_MODULE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "baremodule":
        Return TOKEN_BAREMODULE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "using":
        Return TOKEN_USING
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "import":
        Return TOKEN_IMPORT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "export":
        Return TOKEN_EXPORT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "public":
        Return TOKEN_PUBLIC
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "const":
        Return TOKEN_CONST
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "global":
        Return TOKEN_GLOBAL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "local":
        Return TOKEN_LOCAL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "quote":
        Return TOKEN_QUOTE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "macro":
        Return TOKEN_MACRO
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "where":
        Return TOKEN_WHERE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "in":
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "isa":
        Return TOKEN_ISA
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "true":
        Return TOKEN_TRUE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "false":
        Return TOKEN_FALSE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "nothing":
        Return TOKEN_NOTHING
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Numeric literal lexer handling Julia's full numeric syntax: ints,
floats (with decimal point or e-notation exponent), hex (0x), octal
(0o), and binary (0b) prefixes, and the trailing type suffixes
(0x10u8, 1.5f0). The branching is large but bounded - each prefix
selects a separate sub-loop that recognises only the digits valid in
that base.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads start character to dispatch on prefix: 0x/0X -> hex digits
(0-9, a-f, A-F); 0o/0O -> octal (0-7); 0b/0B -> binary (0-1);
otherwise decimal. Consumes digits greedily. Optional "." with more
digits promotes to float. Optional "e"/"E" with sign + digits is an
exponent. Final suffix (u8, i32, f0, ...) sets the precise type.
Constructs a token via create_token with the computed type and
lexeme span.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_number" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize Julia number literal

    @Reasoning:
    Julia supports: integers, floats, scientific notation, hex, binary, octal,
    complex numbers (im suffix), and rational numbers (// operator handled separately).
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let is_hex be 0
    Let is_binary be 0
    Let is_octal be 0

    Note: Check for 0x (hex), 0b (binary), 0o (octal)
    If ch is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer

        If next_ch is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' (hex)
            Set is_hex to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip '0'
            proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip 'x'
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 98:  Note: 'b' (binary)
            Set is_binary to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 111:  Note: 'o' (octal)
            Set is_octal to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Consume digits. `scanning` drives the loop so it always terminates:
    Note: every iteration either advances the cursor (consuming one number byte)
    Note: or clears `scanning` to exit. A `While 1 is equal to 1` form would
    Note: never exit because there is no break statement in this language form.
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer

        Let is_valid_digit be 0

        If is_hex is equal to 1:
            Note: Hex digit: 0-9, A-F, a-f
            If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
                Set is_valid_digit to 1
            End If
            If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
                If ch is less than or equal to 70:  Note: 'F'
                    Set is_valid_digit to 1
                End If
            End If
            If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
                If ch is less than or equal to 102:  Note: 'f'
                    Set is_valid_digit to 1
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If is_binary is equal to 1:
                Note: Binary digit: 0-1
                If ch is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
                    Set is_valid_digit to 1
                End If
                If ch is equal to 49:  Note: '1'
                    Set is_valid_digit to 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                If is_octal is equal to 1:
                    Note: Octal digit: 0-7
                    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
                        If ch is less than or equal to 55:
                            Set is_valid_digit to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Decimal digit
                    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
                        Set is_valid_digit to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Also allow underscores in numbers (Julia feature)
        If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
            Set is_valid_digit to 1
        End If

        Note: A single decimal point is consumed inline (only for decimal
        Note: numbers) and ends this digit-class iteration without a second
        Note: advance, so the fractional digits are picked up on the next pass.
        Let consumed_dot be 0
        If is_valid_digit is equal to 0:
            If is_hex is equal to 0:
                If is_binary is equal to 0:
                    If is_octal is equal to 0:
                        If ch is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Set consumed_dot to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If is_valid_digit is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If consumed_dot is equal to 0:
                Set scanning to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check for scientific notation (e or E)
    Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer

    If ch is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
        proc advance_char with lexer

        Note: Optional sign
        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        If ch is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        Note: Consume exponent digits
        Let exp_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let exp_is_digit be proc is_digit with exp_ch
        While exp_is_digit is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set exp_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
            Set exp_is_digit to proc is_digit with exp_ch
        End While
    End If

    If ch is equal to 69:  Note: 'E'
        proc advance_char with lexer

        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 43:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
        If ch is equal to 45:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        Let exp2_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let exp2_is_digit be proc is_digit with exp2_ch
        While exp2_is_digit is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set exp2_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
            Set exp2_is_digit to proc is_digit with exp2_ch
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check for 'im' suffix (complex number)
    Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer

    If ch is equal to 105:  Note: 'i'
        Set next_ch to proc peek_next_char with lexer

        If next_ch is equal to 109:  Note: 'm'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Extract lexeme
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, lexeme, line, column, length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
String literal lexer handling Julia's string syntax including
interpolation ("$var"), triple-quoted multi-line strings, raw
strings, byte strings, and escape sequences. The delimiter
parameter lets the same routine handle "..." (default) and
'...' (character literal) by varying the close character.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes characters until the matching delimiter is found, handling
backslash escapes (\n, \t, \\, \", \xHH, \uHHHH). Tracks newlines
via advance_line for multi-line strings. On EOF before close,
emits TOKEN_ERROR. Builds the lexeme span (excluding outer quotes)
and constructs the token via create_token.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_string" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer, delimiter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize Julia string literal

    @Reasoning:
    Julia strings can be: "regular", """triple-quoted""", or raw"raw strings".
    Strings support interpolation with $ and $(expr).
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip opening delimiter

    Note: Check for triple-quoted string
    Let is_triple be 0
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer

    If ch is equal to delimiter:
        Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer

        If next_ch is equal to delimiter:
            Set is_triple to 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Consume string content. `scanning` drives the loop so it always
    Note: terminates: it is cleared at EOF and after the closing delimiter is
    Note: consumed; every other path advances the cursor by at least one byte.
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:  Note: EOF terminates an unclosed string
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            Note: Check for closing delimiter
            If ch is equal to delimiter:
                If is_triple is equal to 1:
                    Note: Check for triple delimiter
                    Let n1 be proc peek_next_char with lexer
                    Let source_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                    Set pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                    Let n2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source_ptr, pos plus 2

                    If n1 is equal to delimiter:
                        If n2 is equal to delimiter:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                            Set scanning to 0  Note: closed triple-quoted string
                        Otherwise:
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip closing delimiter
                    Set scanning to 0  Note: closed single-delimited string
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Handle escape sequences
                If ch is equal to 92:  Note: backslash
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                    Note: Skip escaped character
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Extract lexeme
    Set pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, lexeme, line, column, length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Macro Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier lexer. Reads alpha-start identifier, then continues
through is_alphanumeric characters. After collecting the lexeme,
calls check_keyword to upgrade the token type to a keyword
constant if the lexeme matches one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks while peek_char is_alphanumeric, advancing the cursor each
iteration. Materialises the lexeme substring at start_pos..position,
then calls check_keyword for type classification and constructs the
token via create_token.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_identifier" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize Julia identifier

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Consume alphanumeric characters
    Let wch1 be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let wres1 be proc is_alphanumeric with wch1
    While wres1 is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set wch1 to proc peek_char with lexer
        Set wres1 to proc is_alphanumeric with wch1
    End While

    Note: Extract lexeme
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length

    Note: Check if keyword
    Let token_type be proc check_keyword with lexeme

    Return proc create_token with token_type, lexeme, line, column, length
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia macro invocations use "@name" syntax. The lexer captures the
leading "@" plus the macro name as a single TOKEN_MACRO so the
parser can dispatch on macro calls distinctly from ordinary function
calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the leading "@" then walks is_alphanumeric for the macro
name. Materialises the lexeme substring (including the "@"
character) and creates a TOKEN_MACRO token.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_macro" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize Julia macro name (@macro)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip '@'

    Note: Consume macro name
    Let wch2 be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let wres2 be proc is_alphanumeric with wch2
    While wres2 is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set wch2 to proc peek_char with lexer
        Set wres2 to proc is_alphanumeric with wch2
    End While

    Note: Extract lexeme (including @)
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MACRO_NAME, lexeme, line, column, length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Symbol Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Julia operator/punctuation lexer. Handles single-char operators
(+, -, *, /, %, ^, =, <, >, !, ~, &, |, ., ,, ;, :) plus their
multi-char extensions (==, !=, <=, >=, ..., ::, ->, =>, &&, ||, etc).
The multi-char tokens are detected by checking peek_next_char before
committing to the single-char interpretation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the start character, then uses peek_next_char to detect the
common multi-char extensions. Dispatches to the correct TOKEN_*
constant. Builds the lexeme span and creates the token. Falls
through to TOKEN_ERROR for unrecognised characters.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_symbol" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize Julia symbol (:symbol)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip ':'

    Note: Check if quoted symbol :'symbol' or :"symbol"
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer

    If ch is equal to 39:  Note: single quote
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer, start_pos, 39
    End If

    If ch is equal to 34:  Note: double quote
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer, start_pos, 34
    End If

    Note: Consume symbol name
    If proc is_alpha with ch is equal to 1:
        Let wch3 be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let wres3 be proc is_alphanumeric with wch3
        While wres3 is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set wch3 to proc peek_char with lexer
            Set wres3 to proc is_alphanumeric with wch3
        End While
    End If

    Note: Extract lexeme (including :)
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SYMBOL, lexeme, line, column, length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Main lexer step function. Skips whitespace and comments, then
dispatches on the first non-whitespace character to the appropriate
tokeniser. EOF returns a TOKEN_EOF marker rather than null so
callers can use a uniform end-condition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops skipping whitespace (via is_whitespace + advance_char) and
newlines (via is_newline + advance_line). Skips "#" line comments
and "#=...=#" block comments. After skip, if at EOF returns
TOKEN_EOF. Otherwise reads the first character to dispatch:
is_digit -> tokenize_number; is_alpha or _ -> tokenize_identifier;
quote -> tokenize_string; @ -> tokenize_macro; otherwise ->
tokenize_symbol. Returns the produced token.
@End Implementation
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    @Reasoning:
    Main tokenization loop handling all Julia tokens including operators,
    literals, keywords, and special syntax.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Skip whitespace
    Let wch4 be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let wres4 be proc is_whitespace with wch4
    While wres4 is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set wch4 to proc peek_char with lexer
        Set wres4 to proc is_whitespace with wch4
    End While

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Check EOF
    If pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, "", line, column, 0
    End If

    Let start_pos be pos
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer

    Note: Skip comments
    If ch is equal to 35:  Note: #
        Note: Single-line comment
        Let wch5 be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let wres5 be proc is_newline with wch5
        While wres5 is equal to 0:
            Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
            If c is equal to 0:
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, "", line, column, 0
            End If
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set wch5 to proc peek_char with lexer
            Set wres5 to proc is_newline with wch5
        End While

        Note: Recursively get next token
        Return proc next_token with lexer
    End If

    Note: Handle newlines (Julia cares about newlines for semicolon insertion)
    If proc is_newline with ch is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        proc advance_line with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, "\n", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc tokenize_number with lexer, start_pos
    End If

    Note: Strings
    If ch is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer, start_pos, 34
    End If

    Note: Characters
    If ch is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer, start_pos, 39
    End If

    Note: Command literals
    If ch is equal to 96:  Note: `
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer, start_pos, 96
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    If proc is_alpha with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc tokenize_identifier with lexer, start_pos
    End If

    Note: Macros
    If ch is equal to 64:  Note: @
        Return proc tokenize_macro with lexer, start_pos
    End If

    Note: Symbols
    If ch is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Note: Check if :: (type annotation) or :
        Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer

        If next_ch is equal to 58:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "::", line, column, 2
        End If

        Note: Check if : is part of range (1:10)
        If proc is_digit with next_ch is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, ":", line, column, 1
        End If

        Note: Otherwise it's a symbol
        Return proc tokenize_symbol with lexer, start_pos
    End If

    Note: Operators and delimiters
    Note: Single-character tokens first, then multi-character
    Set next_ch to proc peek_next_char with lexer

    Note: Dot operators (.+, .*, ./, etc.)
    If ch is equal to 46:  Note: .
        If next_ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_PLUS, ".+", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_MINUS, ".-", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 42:  Note: *
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_STAR, ".*", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 47:  Note: /
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_SLASH, "./", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 92:  Note: backslash
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_BACKSLASH, ".\\", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 94:  Note: ^
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_CARET, ".^", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 39:  Note: ' (dot transpose)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT_TRANSPOSE, ".'", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 46:  Note: Check for ...
            Let source_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let third_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source_ptr, pos plus 2

            If third_ch is equal to 46:
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TRIPLE_DOT, "...", line, column, 3
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, ".", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Comparison and assignment operators
    If ch is equal to 61:  Note: =
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: ==
            Set source_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Set third_ch to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source_ptr, pos plus 2

            If third_ch is equal to 61:  Note: ===
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TRIPLE_EQUAL, "===", line, column, 3
            End If

            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUAL, "==", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: =>
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PAIR_ARROW, "=>", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ASSIGN, "=", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Arithmetic operators with assignment variants
    If ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: +=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS_ASSIGN, "+=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS, "+", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: ->
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ARROW, "->", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: -=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS_ASSIGN, "-=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS, "-", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 42:  Note: *
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: *=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR_ASSIGN, "*=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR, "*", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 47:  Note: /
        If next_ch is equal to 47:  Note: //
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_SLASH, "//", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: /=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SLASH_ASSIGN, "/=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SLASH, "/", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 92:  Note: backslash
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BACKSLASH, "\\", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 37:  Note: %
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: %=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PERCENT_ASSIGN, "%=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PERCENT, "%", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 94:  Note: ^
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: ^=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CARET_ASSIGN, "^=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CARET, "^", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Comparison operators
    If ch is equal to 33:  Note: !
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: !=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, "!=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NOT, "!", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 60:  Note: <
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: <=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, "<=", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 60:  Note: <<
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT, "<<", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 124:  Note: <| (backward pipe)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT, "<|", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS, "<", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: >=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, ">=", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: >>
            Set source_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Set third_ch to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source_ptr, pos plus 2

            If third_ch is equal to 62:  Note: >>>
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_UNSIGNED_RIGHT_SHIFT, ">>>", line, column, 3
            End If

            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT, ">>", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER, ">", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Logical and bitwise operators
    If ch is equal to 38:  Note: &
        If next_ch is equal to 38:  Note: &&
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AND, "&&", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: &=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AND_ASSIGN, "&=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BIT_AND, "&", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 124:  Note: |
        If next_ch is equal to 124:  Note: ||
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_OR, "||", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: |> (forward pipe)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT, "|>", line, column, 2
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: |=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_OR_ASSIGN, "|=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BIT_OR, "|", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 126:  Note: ~
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BIT_NOT, "~", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 8853:  Note: ⊻ (xor symbol minus Unicode)
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: ⊻=
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_XOR_ASSIGN, "⊻=", line, column, 2
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BIT_XOR, "⊻", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Delimiters
    If ch is equal to 40:  Note: (
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "(", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 41:  Note: )
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, ")", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, "[", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, "]", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE, "{", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE, "}", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, ",", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, ";", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 63:  Note: ?
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_QUESTION, "?", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 36:  Note: $
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOLLAR, "$", line, column, 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 39:  Note: ' (transpose)
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TRANSPOSE, "'", line, column, 1
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    proc advance_char with lexer
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, "?", line, column, 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Tokenization Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Drives the lexer to completion, collecting all tokens into a list.
The public entry point for the frontend - callers receive a fully
tokenised input ready for the parser to consume.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an empty List. Loops calling next_token; appends each
result to the list. Continues until a TOKEN_EOF is encountered
(the TOKEN_EOF itself is also appended so the parser has an explicit
end marker). Returns the token list pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire source into token array

    @Reasoning:
    Collects all tokens into an array for parser consumption.
    Dynamically grows the token array as needed.
    @End Reasoning

    Let capacity be 1000
    Let count be 0
    Let tokens be proc allocate from Layout with capacity multiplied by 8

    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let done be 0
    While done is equal to 0:
        Let token be proc next_token with lexer

        If token is equal to 0:
            Note: Defensive: next_token always yields a TOKEN_EOF token at
            Note: end of input, but if allocation inside it failed we stop.
            Set done to 1
        Otherwise:
            Note: Resize if needed
            If count is greater than or equal to capacity:
                Let new_capacity be capacity multiplied by 2
                Let new_tokens be proc allocate from Layout with new_capacity multiplied by 8

                If new_tokens is equal to 0:
                    Return tokens
                End If

                proc memory_copy from Layout with new_tokens, tokens, count multiplied by 8
                proc deallocate from Layout with tokens

                Set tokens to new_tokens
                Set capacity to new_capacity
            End If

            Note: Store token
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with tokens, count multiplied by 8, token

            Set count to count plus 1

            Note: TOKEN_EOF is the real terminator; once stored we stop.
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF:
                Set done to 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return tokens
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience accessor for the total token count. Used by tests and
diagnostics to verify the expected number of tokens was produced.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Drives next_token across the lexer until a TOKEN_EOF token is produced,
counting every token (the terminating TOKEN_EOF included) so the result
matches the length of the array tokenize would build for the same lexer.
The lexer's cursor advances as a side effect, so callers pass a fresh
lexer when they intend to re-tokenize afterwards.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_token_count" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Count tokens by running the same scan tokenize uses.

    @Reasoning:
    This tracks the total number of tokens produced during tokenization.
    Useful for memory allocation and parser initialization.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_count be 0
    Let done be 0

    While done is equal to 0:
        Let token be proc next_token with lexer

        If token is equal to 0:
            Set done to 1
        Otherwise:
            Set token_count to token_count plus 1
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF:
                Set done to 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return token_count
End Process
